[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926858&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926858&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Domain names *are* host names. The restriction in RFC882 says that no
"label" (the parts of a domain name between the dots) can begin in a
non-alpha (that is, "foo.3com.com" is just as illegal as "3com.com").
It is certainly possible that 3com.com, as a vendor of TCP/IP products,
might join the internet one day, just as Proteon and ACC have.

So far as I can see, this restriction is a continuation of the host
table definition (currently RFC952), which prohibits hostnames from
beginning in a digit (in the very first page no less!). I had to look
this particular RFC over rather carefully last spring when some BU
machines got registered with computer-type names that began in digits
(3B5), which broke the 4.2 BSD "htable" program, to decide whether I
should fix htable or complain to the NIC. As I recall, the question
was ambiguous (w.r.t. computer-type names), and so I fixed htable.

	Erik E. Fair	ucbvax!fair	fair@ucbarpa.berkeley.edu

